<!--*********************************************
            Solution
**********************************************-->  
<solution>
  <p>Note that there are multiple ways to tackle this problem. Here is one possible approach</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Since we have a <math>sec(theta) = 1/cos(theta)</math> in the denominator, and a <math>tan(theta) = sin(theta)/cos(theta)</math> in the numerator, try to cancel out the <math>cos(theta)</math>'s somehow. Multiply both numerator and denominator by <m>\cos(\theta)</m>,
      <me><math>tan(theta)*cos(theta)/((sec(theta) - cos(theta))cos(theta))</math></me>
    </li>
    <li>
To illustrate how this helps us, rewrite <m>\tan(\theta)</m> and <m>\sec(\theta)</m> from their definitions,
      <me><math>sin(theta)/cos(theta) cos(theta)/((1/cos(theta) - cos(theta))cos(theta))</math></me>
    </li>
    <li>Now, we can cancel out those <m>\cos(\theta)</m>'s in the denominators top and bottom,
      <me><math>sin(theta)/(1 - cos^2(theta))</math></me>
    </li>
    <li>Now, notice that the denominator can be simplified further, since <math>sin^2(theta) + cos^2(theta) = 1</math>,
      <me><math>sin(theta)/(sin^2(theta)) = 1/sin(theta)</math></me>
    </li>
    <li>Finally, by definition, <math>1/sin(theta) = csc(theta)</math></li>
  </ul>
 
</solution>
</problem>
